english:
  title: A Dream's Verification
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    To speak of dreams may seem strange and fanciful. Yet the Zhou officials recorded six types of dream divination, and throughout the Five Classics and the writings of philosophers and historians, dreams are frequently mentioned. If dreams can truly bear witness to coming events, what harm is there in recounting them?

    It happened when I once held the post of Record-Keeper in Wansan. In those days, I rarely visited the City God's shrine. One night I dreamed I had gone to that shrine and bowed in the courtyard, as if standing beside the magistrate's officer. The divine King sent word through a messenger: "Will the Record-Keeper not ascend the steps?" I climbed to the great hall and bowed twice. The King, dressed in a cloth cap and black linen robe, rose from his seat at the south end to return my bow, then beckoned me forward. Soon someone brought white wine and poured it. The cup and table were humble, yet we drank together for a long time. The King spoke: "I hear the magistrate has recently had twelve histories newly printed. Is this so?" I replied, "It is." He said, "Why then have you not sent me any? I have many children and wish them to read these books. Could you spare a few volumes?" I answered, "Of course." Then he added, "There is a certain official, the chief among the ranks, called So-and-so. He is a capable man. I ask that you watch over him." Again I said, "I shall." I also asked about my fortune and misfortune. The King pointed to a cart on the road whose axle had broken and said, "Your fate is like that cart's. Before this year ends, you shall depart from this province." Then he brought forth two leather belts and gave them to me, saying, "You shall surely rise to honor. I give you these as provisions for your journey."

    When I woke, my whole body was damp with sweat. At that time, the Provincial Inspector, General Lu, had the magistrate print twelve histories newly. Moreover, a certain official displeased me, and I wished to remove him through some pretext. Such was my thinking then. The next day I summoned the official and had two copies of the printed histories sent as an offering to the shrine, and I pardoned his offense without further inquiry. That very year I was indeed dismissed through the accusations of my colleagues—then I understood the King's words about the broken axle. Yet for seven years I lived in obscurity, unable to secure even a single post, and my circumstances grew most dire. Thus I ceased to believe his words. Later, though I served in various important positions and rose to the third rank, still I did not deeply trust them. But when at last I received appointment as Prime Minister, only then did I truly believe in his promise that I should rise to great honor—it matched the words as perfectly as a seal meets its impression.

    Ah! The subtle workings of the divine realm do sometimes prove true. How can we dismiss them as mere illusion?

    Written in the twelfth month of the Year of Gapoh.
